S-s-h, the secure shell.

S-s-h, the secure shell, is how you log into a remote linux machine and run commands as though you were sitting at its console. It encrypts everything that passes between the two ends, authenticates both sides, and is the universal administration protocol, used the same way on every linux box, every cloud provider, and every container. There are two ends to it: the client, which is the s-s-h command you run on your own machine, and the server, the s-s-h daemon running on the remote machine, listening on tee-see-pee port twenty-two by default.

Basic usage is simple: you give the s-s-h command a username and a host, and it logs you in. You can add a flag for a custom port, point it at a specific key file, hand it a single command to run and then exit instead of giving you a shell, or ask it to allocate a pseudo-terminal, which you need when a remote sudo prompt is involved. Without a port flag it always connects to port twenty-two; some security-conscious sites move s-s-h to a different port to cut down scanner noise, though the real protection is good keys, not an unusual port.

There is one thing worth understanding early: host key verification. The first time you connect to a machine, s-s-h shows you that host's fingerprint and asks whether to continue. This is your defence against a man-in-the-middle attack, so on that first connection you should verify the fingerprint through some other channel, by asking the administrator or checking a cloud console. Once you accept it, the key is stored in your known-hosts file and checked silently on every later connection. And if you ever see a loud warning that the remote host identification has changed, do not blindly accept it; it means the host's key is different from last time, usually because the server was rebuilt, but possibly something worse, so verify the new key before trusting it.
